{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633491"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:53:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:53:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17479"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10169"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56189"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7787"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23787"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA study examines the relationship between smoking and lung cancer. The following data were collected:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncidence of lung cancer in smokers: 60 cases per 100,000 person-years\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncidence of lung cancer in non-smokers: 5 cases per 100,000 person-years\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the attributable risk of lung cancer due to smoking in this population?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["55 cases per 100,000 person-years","30 cases per 100,000 person-years","5 cases per 100,000 person-years","65 cases per 100,000 person-years","12 cases per 100,000 person-years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe attributable risk is calculated by subtracting the incidence rate in the unexposed group from the incidence rate in the exposed group:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAttributable Risk = Incidence in exposed - Incidence in unexposed\u003Cbr /\u003E= 60 per 100,000 - 5 per 100,000\u003Cbr /\u003E= \u003Cstrong\u003E55 cases per 100,000 person-years\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAttributable risk is an important measure in epidemiology because it:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQuantifies the absolute effect of an exposure on disease occurrence\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHelps determine the potential impact of prevention strategies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIs expressed in the same units as the original incidence rates, making it easily interpretable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECan be used to calculate the number of cases that could be prevented by eliminating the exposure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike relative risk, which shows the strength of an association, attributable risk shows the absolute magnitude of the effect and is therefore more useful for public health planning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Attributable risk measures the excess risk of disease in exposed individuals compared to unexposed individuals.","Attributable risk is calculated by subtracting the incidence rate in the unexposed group from the incidence rate in the exposed group.","A higher attributable risk indicates a stronger association between exposure and disease occurrence.","Attributable risk is expressed in the same units as the incidence rates."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56189"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17479"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56189"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:33:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:34:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10169"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70723"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","nam